message.content: We refer to PubMed articles on medicine for help. During the second trimester, fetal myelopoiesis primarily occurs in the liver. The yolk sac is the site of early hematopoiesis, but it is replaced by the liver during the second trimester. The aorta-gonad-mesonephros region and spleen play roles in fetal hematopoiesis but not myelopoiesis specifically.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. At this stage of development, the primary location for fetal myelopoiesis is the liver. The yolk sac is the site of early hematopoiesis, but it is replaced by the liver and spleen by the second trimester. The aorta-gonad-mesonephros region is the site of hematopoiesis during the first few weeks of gestation. The spleen is a site of extramedullary hematopoiesis, but it is not the primary site for fetal myelopoiesis.
